For this text analysis lab I wanted to look at and compare song lyrics from 1965 and 2015 and see if there were any similarities in the word choice for the song lyrics. I used data that compiled the song lyrics of Billboard’s top 100 pop songs for those years. Because the songs are a part of completely different eras the words used in these song lyrics I believe will reflect those times and the culture for those years.

lyrics <- data_frame(file = paste0(c("lyrics_1965.txt", "lyrics_2015.txt"))) %>%
  mutate(text = map(file, read_lines)) %>%
  unnest() %>%
  group_by(file = str_sub(basename(file), 1, -5)) %>%
  mutate(line_number = row_number()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)  %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  mutate(word = wordStem(word)) 

head(lyrics)

Here I count each word per all the song lyrics for each year.

lw = lyrics[ ,c("file","word")]
d =  count_(lw, c("file", "word"))

Below I made a document term matrix.

lwdtm = d %>%
  cast_dtm(file, word, n)

Below I converted the document term matrix into a dataframe so I could have a better look at the different terms used in all of the song lyrics from 2015 and 1965 and how many times each term occurs in each year.

mlwdtm=as.matrix(lwdtm)
df.mlwdtm=as.data.frame(mlwdtm)


t.t = t(mlwdtm)

Below we can look at the most distinctive words for all of the songs for the year 1965 and 2015.

df.t.t = as.data.frame(t.t)

summing = function(x) x/sum(x, na.rm=T)

df.t.t.2 = apply(df.t.t, 2, summing)

df.t.t$names<-rownames(df.t.t)

I ran a Pearson correlation to look at how correlated the lyrics from 1965 and 2015 are. Below is the Pearson correlation coefficient for the two years, which we can see is 0.74.

cor(t.t, method="pearson")
##             lyrics_1965 lyrics_2015
## lyrics_1965   1.0000000   0.7422291
## lyrics_2015   0.7422291   1.0000000

I also ran the cosine correlation below which we can see shows that the song lyrics of 1965 and 2015 have a cosine similarity of 0.75.

#install.packages("lsa")
library(lsa)
cosine(t.t)
##             lyrics_1965 lyrics_2015
## lyrics_1965   1.0000000   0.7549545
## lyrics_2015   0.7549545   1.0000000

I also ran a Chi-squared test below to measure the song lyrics similarities. The Chi-squared test has a value of 163247. The p-value for the test is less than the significance level of 0.05 which suggests that the song lyrics from 1965 and 2015 are not independent.

ctable <- table(t.t)
chisq.test(ctable)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  ctable
## X-squared = 163247, df = 85, p-value < 2.2e-16

Below I also looked at the term frequency inverse year frequency. So I isolated the words that are most associated with one year or the other.

d= df.mlwdtm
idf <- log(nrow(d)/colSums(d))
tfidf <- d
for(word in names(idf)){
  tfidf[,word] <- df.mlwdtm[,word] * idf[word]
}

head(round(tfidf, 2))
m.tfidf=as.matrix(tfidf)
df.m.tfidf=as.data.frame(m.tfidf)
## make the dtm into a tdm instead ##

t.df.m.tfidf = t(df.m.tfidf)

t.df.m.tfidf=as.data.frame(t.df.m.tfidf)

head(t.df.m.tfidf, 25)
cor(t.df.m.tfidf, method="pearson")
##             lyrics_1965 lyrics_2015
## lyrics_1965   1.0000000   0.8052943
## lyrics_2015   0.8052943   1.0000000

Looking at the table above we can see the inverse weightings for the song lyrics of the two years.

Based on these inverse weightings I also found the Pearson correlation is .80 which means that there is a slightly strong and positive relationship between the song lyrics in the two years.

I decided to create word clouds to look at the most common words in song lyrics of 1965 and 2015.

Below is the word cloud for all of the lyrics from Billboard’s top 100 songs in 1965

Below is the word cloud for all of the lyrics from Billboard’s top 100 songs in 2015

wordcloud(df.t.t$names, df.t.t$lyrics_2015, min.freq=10, random.color=T, ordered.colors=T)

In the above 2015 word cloud we can see several explicit words that are larger and that do not appear in the 1965 word cloud, suggesting maybe that our culture is more desensitized towards these explicit words.

Lastly, I decided to conduct a sentiment analysis looking at all of the positive and negative words in the song lyrics for 1965 and 2015. Below I first look at how many words in the song lyrics of 1965 had a positive connotation and how many had a negative connotation.

lyrics_sentiment <- inner_join(lyrics, get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  filter(file == "lyrics_1965") %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  summarise(word_count = n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(sentiment = reorder(sentiment, word_count))
sentimentplot1 <- lyrics_sentiment %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sentiment, word_count, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col() +
  guides(fill = FALSE) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Word Count") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 550)) +
  ggtitle("1965 Song Lyrics Sentiment") +
  coord_flip()


sentimentplot1

In the above plot we can see that 1965 song lyrics had more positive words than negative.

Then I looked at how many words in the song lyrics of 2015 had a positive connotation and how many had a negative connotation.

lyrics_sentiment2 <- inner_join(lyrics, get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  filter(file == "lyrics_2015") %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  summarise(word_count = n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(sentiment = reorder(sentiment, word_count))


sentimentplot2 <- lyrics_sentiment2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sentiment, word_count, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col() +
  guides(fill = FALSE) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Word Count") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1500)) +
  ggtitle("2015 Song Lyrics Sentiment") +
  coord_flip()


sentimentplot2

In the above plot we can see that the song lyrics from 2015 had more words with a negative connotation than positive.

Overall, I wouldn’t say either year was more negative or positive in the songs meaning and both years had similar counts for commonly used words, however there was a much greater number of explicit words used in 2015. Additionally, this analysis also helped to show that there was a shift in the types of songs people listened to in likely connected with.
